---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'How to Drink Baijiu Without Wasting It';
const description = 'Learn how to serve, smell, sip, toast, and pair baijiu so the drink makes sense instead of feeling like a harsh challenge.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <header class="article-header"><div class="narrow"><p class="eyebrow">Serving Guide</p><h1>How to Drink Baijiu</h1><p class="lede">Baijiu is often served in tiny cups, but that does not mean the only way to drink it is to throw it back without tasting.</p></div></header>
  <section class="content"><article>
    <h2>Use Small Pours</h2><p>Small cups help manage intensity. Smell first, take a small sip, and let the aroma unfold with food.</p>
    <h2>Pair With Food</h2><p>Baijiu often works better with meals than alone. Rich meat, spicy dishes, grilled foods, pickles, and savory sauces can make strong aromas feel more integrated.</p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Style</th><th>Food direction</th><th>Why it helps</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Sauce aroma</td><td>Roasted meat, fermented sauces, mushrooms, rich braises</td><td>Savory food makes the fermented depth feel intentional <a href="/db/aroma/sauce/">(browse sauce varieties)</a></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Strong aroma</td><td>Spicy Sichuan dishes, grilled skewers, fatty pork, pickles</td><td>Fruit and cellar notes stand up to bold seasoning <a href="/db/aroma/strong/">(browse strong varieties)</a></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Light aroma</td><td>Dumplings, cold dishes, simple grilled foods</td><td>Cleaner grain notes do not need heavy sauces <a href="/db/aroma/light/">(browse light varieties)</a></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Rice aroma</td><td>Seafood, vegetables, lighter southern dishes</td><td>Softer aroma is easier to overwhelm</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <h2>Understand Toasting</h2><p>In banquet settings, baijiu can carry social meaning. You do not need to imitate every drinking rhythm blindly. Pace, politeness, and clarity matter. If you are planning a trip, ChinaTripBox's guide to <a href="https://www.chinatripbox.com/posts/tipping-in-china-when-it-s-expected-and-when-it-s-not/">tipping and service expectations in China</a> helps explain the wider restaurant etiquette context around bills, service, and host-guest roles.</p>
    <h2>Try Cocktails Carefully</h2><p>Rice aroma and some light/strong aroma bottles can work in cocktails, but intense sauce aroma can dominate a drink. Use it like a powerful flavor ingredient.</p>
    <div class="faq">
      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <h3>Should baijiu be chilled?</h3>
      <p>Most traditional baijiu service is at room temperature. Chilling can reduce alcohol heat, but it also hides aroma, which is the point of the drink.</p>
      <h3>Do I have to finish every toast?</h3>
      <p>No. Social expectations vary, but clear pacing and polite refusal are better than drinking beyond your limit.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="next-links">
      <a href="/types-of-baijiu/">Back to aroma types</a>
      <a href="/best-baijiu-for-beginners/">Choose a bottle for this use case</a>
      <a href="/db/">Explore the baijiu database</a>
    </div>
  </article></section>
</BaseLayout>
